         <head xml:lang="en"/>
         <div type="commentary" subtype="frontmatter" xml:space="preserve"><p>Medical recipes. Papyrus sheet (23.5 x 14 cm) containing on the <emph rend="italics">recto</emph> two receipts separated by a horizontal line: the first remedy (ll. 1-14) is a plaster (ἔμπλαστρος) for the stomach; the second is a famous eye-salve made from roses (κολλύριον διάροδ[ο]ν), which is well attested in medical literature (see <emph rend="italics">e.g.</emph> Gal. <emph rend="italics">Comp.med.sec.loc.</emph> 4.7 [12, 767.12-768.10 K]; Orib. <emph rend="italics">Syn</emph>. 3.158 [106.15-20 Raed.]). On the <emph rend="italics">verso</emph> (<emph rend="italics">transversa charta</emph>), the headings of both recipes are copied with some variants. The hand is a semi-cursive <emph rend="italics">Geschäftsschrift</emph> assignable to the second half of the 5th cent. AD.</p></div>
